title: For Sale:  US WWII 60mm Mortar black powder set up
postcontent:
Selling my black powder US M2 60mm mortar set.

See my photobucket site for a bunch of photos.

http://s214.photobucket.com/user/R_S_Hubbard/library/Mortar?sort=2&page=1

The cup is a repro, no markings or pin.

Custom made inner barrel liner.

Outside barrel is probably a repro but frankly I'm not sure. I see no markings on it so I expect it's a repro. Inside diameter is 2.359"/ 60mm so maybe it is original. The liner is 1.935"/ 50mm.

The legs are WWII. See dataplate; 1945 dates.

The base plate is original.

Sight is USGI; can't recall the date. With aluminum case, strap.

Two web / leather carrying straps; one for show, one for go.

Custom made storage / transport crate. It all fits in there.

I have about 100 ready-made custom rounds for this mortar. They each consist of a flame-lit fuse that ignites the propellant charge, which propels the plastic bottle full of sand and fused explosive charge. Kind of like an M80 internal charge but it's not really loud or dangerous as it is enclosed in sand, all inside the small plastic bottle / 'mortar round'. These are NOT INCLUDED IN THIS AUCTION but will be made available to the winner. I do not want to make a tough shipping scenario worse by trying to also ship fireworks – which is also very troublesome and costly.

Folks, I really do not want to try to ship this. It's heavy. I'd probably need to make a crate, which makes it even heavier and more expensive. Some sort of direct pickup would be best. However, if it needs to be shipped, the mortar and crate will need to go freight. This is up to the buyer to arrange. You pay the first $150; I’ll pay up to $100 after that. If it costs more than $250, all the rest is your responsibility.

title: For Sale:  Very Rare 1865 Smith and Wesson Buy Back Model 1 .32 Long Rimfire Pistol
postcontent:
The Smith & Wesson Model 1 was the first firearm manufactured by Smith & Wesson, with production spanning the years 1857 through 1882. It was the first commercially successful revolver to use rimfire cartridges instead of loose powder, musket ball, and percussion caps. It is a single-action, tip-up revolver.
As Samuel Colt's patent on the revolver was set to expire in 1856, Horace Smith and Daniel B. Wesson were researching a prototype for a metallic cartridge revolver. When they discovered that a former Colt employee named Rollin White held the patent for a "Bored-through" cylinder, a component needed for this new invention, the two partners approached White to manufacture a newly designed revolver-and-cartridge combination.[2]
Rather than make White a partner in their company, Smith and Wesson paid him a royalty of $0.25 on every "Model 1" revolver that they made. It would become White's responsibility to defend his patent in any court cases which eventually led to his financial ruin, but was very advantageous for the new Smith & Wesson Company.
The Model 1 3rd Issue represented a substantial redesign for the Model 1, with a fluted cylinder, a round barrel and a rounded "bird's head" style grip. Finishes included nickel plating (on both the frame and barrel) and blued steel. Produced from 1868 through 1882, the 3rd Issues were serial numbered from 1 through approximately 131,000
The Model 1 was in popular demand with the outbreak of the American Civil War as soldiers from all ranks on both sides of the conflict made private purchases of the revolvers for self-defense. So much that orders for the Model 1 revolver outpaced the factory's production capabilities, forcing Smith & Wesson to expand into a new facility and began experimenting with a new cartridge design more suitable than the .22 Short in 1860
This popularity led to numerous knockoffs and patent infringements by other armsmakers. Rolin White and S&W brought infringement cases against Manhattan Firearms Company, Ethan Allen, Merwin & Bray, National Arms Company and others. The courts mostly allowed these manufacturers to continue production runs, with a royalty on each revolver paid to White. In some cases, Smith & Wesson bought the revolvers back to remark and sell; these are marked "APRIL 3 1855" as a patent date.
